#1 Resected colon adenocarcinoma
Dr. Jenkins is a very pleasant 79 year-old male with metasynchronous resected colon cancer seeking treatment recommendations.
Basic cancer education has been provided to the patient at the request of Dr. Donna Fordyce's  Service.  I have had the opportunity to review the operative report, surgical pathology, laboratory values, and notes in Documents Browser.  I have reviewed these findings with the patient and answered questions.  I have discussed this case in detail with Dr. Gladys Johnson, my collaborating physician, who has guided my plan.
We have discussed the characteristics of the cancer, including the type of malignancy, size, grade, lymph node status, and stage of the cancer.
Dr. Jenkins does not plan on following-up at Montana State Valley Hospital.  Furthermore, we are not recommending any adjuvant chemotherapy in this setting.  I have discussed with him the need for genetic consultation.  I will ask Dr. Johnson to visit with Dr. Jenkins prior to dismissal for formal treatment recommendations.  Certainly, if the need arises in the future, we will be more than happy to help facilitate care.  Dr. Jenkins also notes he has a local medical oncologist in Mount Jewett Pennsylvania that he follows-up with routinely.
PATIENT EDUCATION
Ready to learn, no apparent learning barriers were identified; learning preferences include listening.  Explained diagnosis and treatment plan; patient expressed understanding of the content.

